and exchange, revealing the ways in which these robust social institutions are transformed by an encompassing capitalist economy. Many passenger women assert that they have been treated "olsem maket" (like market goods) by their husbands and natal kin, and they respond by fleeing home and defiantly appropriating their sexuality for their own purposes. Experiences of rape, violence, and the failure of kin to redress such wrongs figure prominently in their own stories about becoming "wayward." Drawing on village court cases, hospital records, and women’s own raw, caustic , and darkly funny narratives, Wayward Women provides a riveting portrait of the way modernity engages with gender to produce new and contested subjectivities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBride pricezPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aCourtshipzPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aWomen, HulixSexual behaviorzPapua New GuineazTari District. 0aWomen, HulizPapua New GuineazTari DistrictxEconomic conditions. 0aWomen, HulizPapua New GuineazTari DistrictxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  abridewealth.  acapitalist economy.  acontemporary papua new guinea.  acourt cases.  aethnography.  afemale agency.  agender issues.  agender studies.  agendered violence.  ahuli women.  amarriage.  amodern world.  anew guinea society.  anonfiction.  apapua new guinea.  apassenger women.  apersonal experiences.  aprostitution.  arape.  asex workers.  asexuality.  asocial institutions.  asocioeconomic factors.  atransactional sex.  avillage law.  awomen and families.  awomen.  awomens roles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz97805202455